        "header": "2Related Work",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2604.11737/2604.11737v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Our approach to learn a dense motion space.Sparse tracker trajectories and the start frame are encoded into a latent motion grid, which enables dense reconstruction at arbitrary spatial query points. The model jointly attends over trajectory tokens and frame features, producing temporally consistent, spatially dense motion predictions.",
                "position": 334
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "3Method",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2604.11737/2604.11737v1/x3.png",
                "caption": "Figure 3:Model architecture to generate in learned motion space.We train a conditional flow matching model that learns a vector field over latent motion grids. We condition on either pokes[7]or text prompts, enabling controllable and semantically coherent motion synthesis in the learned motion space. The frame𝐟0\\mathbf{f}_{0}provides context over the scene.",
                "position": 398
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2604.11737/2604.11737v1/x4.png",
                "caption": "Figure 4:Temporal compression enables our model to generate plausible motions more efficiently. Under a fixed compute budget, both motion generation quality and inference throughput improve substantially with stronger compression (left), with only a minor reduction in reconstruction fidelity (middle). We attribute these gains to the reduced token count, which improves training efficiency, and to an increasingly semantic latent structure, as evidenced by higher kNN retrieval accuracy (right).",
                "position": 537
            }
        ]
    },
